's journalist who delayed and procrastinated or in the subjects of Chardin's paintings who delighted in suspended, playful time, Pierre Saint-Amand shows how eighteenth-century works provided a strong argument for laziness. Rousseau abandoned his previous defense of labor to pursue reverie and botanical walks, Diderot emphasized a parasitic strategy of resisting work in order to liberate time, and Joubert's little-known posthumous Notebooks radically opposed the central philosophy of the Enlightenment in a quest to infinitely postpone work. Unsettling the stubborn view of the eighteenth century as an age of frenetic industriousness and labor, The Pursuit of Laziness plumbs the texts and images of the time and uncovers deliberate yearnings for slowness and recreation.Some images inside the book are unavailable due to digital copyright restrictions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aEnlightenmentxFrance. 0aEnlightenmentzFrance. 0aLazinessxFrance. 0aLaziness. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aBonnet de nuit.  aBulles de savon.  aCartesian thought.  aDenis Diderot.  aDiderot.  aEnlightenment thinking.  aEnlightenment.  aGeorges-Jacques Danton.  aJean-Jacques Rousseau.  aJean-Simon Chardin.  aJoseph Joubert.  aLouis-Sbastien Mercier.  aMichel Foucault.  aPierre Carlet de Marivaux.  aPierre de Marivaux.  aRameau's Nephew.  aalternative subjectivation.  aauthority.  abourgeois.  acontemplation.  adomestic interiors.  adsoeuvrement.  aefficiency.  aeffort.  aeighteenth century.  afunctionality.  aidleness.  aidler.  aindustrialization.  ajournalist.  alabor.  alaziness.  aleisure.  amodernity.  amoralist.  anonproductivity.  aphilosopher.  aphilosophical writings.  aphilosophy.  apillow.  apolitical philosopher.  apo